Fascinating and peaceful
Apr 2024 Couples
Immense cemetery with a wide variety of tombstones, and masterfully crafted almost like little temples or homes. At first, was startled to see into them many coffins of different ages, states of decay, decorative detail, and so on. But gradually became accustomed and really took in the details, like photos of loved ones and intricate stained glass. Go to the end for a view of the bridge. Also was there for the cats, but didnt see any.

JDSV
The Netherlands318 contributions
A cemetery well worth a visit
Jan 2024 Couples
Cemiterio dos Prazeres is the Lisbon equivalent of Paris famous Pre-Lachaise, but without the crowds. While no world famous personalities are buried there, the mausoleums (including the largest in Europe) are works of art, and house the remains of Portuguese nobility, politicians, writers, etc.
The cypress-lined paths are a haven of tranquility and at the far end offer a great view of the 25 April bridge.
The cemetery is in the Campo de Ourique neighborhood, a pleasant tourist-free area.
Written March 5, 2024

Jul 2022
I found the Cemiterio lovely and poignant, but I'm doing research on end-of-life issues. Not recommended for the easily creeped out or those looking for a morbid thrill; these are real mausoleums of real people from real families. If you can be respectful and appreciate the beauty, go for it.
